Bruce, Frank R., since I feel like this all got started somehow
because of me, let me just say that I think a lot of what we were
collectively arguing about may be semantics. We&#39;re all agreed about
pursuing this research in a positive frame of mind. If you have a
naturally positive one, or if you need to do something ritualistic to
remind yourself that you are in a positive mindset, it really doesn&#39;t
matter. The same end is obtained.We&#39;re all okay, no matter which way
we get to the positive vibe. As John Lennon said, &quot;Whatever gets you
through the night, its alright.&quot;

You&#39;re both splendid researchers and you are both right, HMO.

Ann


--- In EVP-ITC@...m, Frank Ratka &lt;warrior18eii@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Bruce,
&gt; 
&gt; No problem, you are entitled to your perspective and opinion. I
really don&#39;t see anywhere in my post, a stance being made beside my
agreeing with Sumption. Since you mentioned it, I have a problem with
people who consider themselves to be advanced researchers in ITC
telling others that there are things you need protection from in this
field. I have seen this fear mongering over the many years I have been
involved with my research and the research of colleagues and
associates and it has never helped anyone. Are there negative entities
out there that want to influence you and distract you? Sure there are!
Probably just as many who want to help you and they have been there
since the beginning of each of our lives.
&gt; 
&gt; The rule of thumb in dealing with those negative forces is to not
follow their messages. If the message is basically negative then give
it no merit and carry on. No ritual needed! Now if you want
credentials I can give you my &quot;paranormal resume&quot; and let the pissing
contest begin. All you need to know about me is I know enough to know
that the more I learn and experience the more I realize I have a lot
to learn. Ego you say, not at all. 
&gt; 
&gt; Best regards,
&gt; 
&gt; Frank R.
